<h2 class="sectionedit4" id="wiki_improvement">Wiki improvement</h2>
<div class="level2">

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit5" id="general">General</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
<em>Please link to forum threads or wiki pages; put links here and content on wiki pages.</em>
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Clean up <a href="http://wiki.openwrt.org/?do=index" class="urlextern" title="http://wiki.openwrt.org/?do=index"  rel="nofollow">wiki root directory</a></div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Move pages that obviously don&#039;t belong there to the correct destination</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> The top-level pages all contain warnings, provisos, and caveats about things that are under construction, or that might not work.<br/>
This would scare away any sensible person.</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> We need to change those top-level pages (and then the rest of the site&#039;s pages) to tell the story of OpenWrt.</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> They must <strong>welcome</strong> new people.</div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> They must let people know that OpenWrt is <strong>easy to use</strong></div>
<ul>
<li class="level3"><div class="li"> Create easy + reliable <strong>guide for beginners</strong></div>
<ul>
<li class="level4"><div class="li"> good example: <a href="https://github.com/EFForg/OpenWireless" class="urlextern" title="https://github.com/EFForg/OpenWireless"  rel="nofollow">https://github.com/EFForg/OpenWireless</a></div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> and inspire confidence that <strong>most anyone can succeed.</strong></div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> The documentation could be &quot;more social&quot;</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> The documentation could be more modern-looking/visually attractive</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Firmware filename should include the version (or build revision for trunk) so that users DO know what they&#039;ve downloaded, even when they check a few months later</div>
</li>
</ul>

</div>

<h4 id="tiers_of_information">Tiers of information</h4>
<div class="level4">

<p>
(from: <a href="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?pid=275612#p275612" class="urlextern" title="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?pid=275612#p275612"  rel="nofollow">https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?pid=275612#p275612</a>)
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Tutorials</strong> illustrate a basic workflow from start to finish. It hand holds the reader through steps. There shouldn&#039;t be any confusion over what the reader should be doing.</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Guides</strong> involve a deep dive of a topic. They&#039;re often cross cutting concerns (like security) which cover multiple areas and deal with conceptual topics. Less guiding but examples of usage may be appropriate.</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>References</strong> are lower level and meticulously describe APIs and data structures.</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>High quality</strong> documentation requires all of them so people in different levels of experience can get access to the knowledge they need to participate.</div>
</li>
</ul>

<p>
⇒ Structure the wiki namespaces accordingly?
</p>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit6" id="toh">ToH</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
<em>Please link to forum threads or wiki pages; put links here and content on wiki pages.</em>
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Forum thread:</strong> <a href="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?id=56521" class="urlextern" title="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?id=56521"  rel="nofollow">Improve the Wiki Table of Hardware</a></div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Improve filtering, searching, sorting, limited columns</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> What can we learn from others? → collect good/bad examples for toh&#039;s (freetz / wehavemorefun / dd-wrt / …) and put links here</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box-Familie" class="urlextern" title="http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box-Familie"  rel="nofollow">http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box-Familie</a></div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <a href="http://dd-wrt.com/site/support/router-database" class="urlextern" title="http://dd-wrt.com/site/support/router-database"  rel="nofollow">http://dd-wrt.com/site/support/router-database</a> (search e.g. &quot;D-Link&quot;; click on a router of your choice)</div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <a href="http://freetz.org/browser/branches/freetz-stable-2.0/FIRMWARES" class="urlextern" title="http://freetz.org/browser/branches/freetz-stable-2.0/FIRMWARES"  rel="nofollow">http://freetz.org/browser/branches/freetz-stable-2.0/FIRMWARES</a> (much smaller pool of devices, therefore a simple list is sufficient)</div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <a href="https://wikidevi.com/wiki/Main_Page" class="urlextern" title="https://wikidevi.com/wiki/Main_Page"  rel="nofollow">https://wikidevi.com/wiki/Main_Page</a></div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <a href="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?pid=275762#p275762" class="urlextern" title="https://forum.openwrt.org/viewtopic.php?pid=275762#p275762"  rel="nofollow">Make table headers fixed while scrolling vertically through the table</a></div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Reason: see <a href="../toh/start#tp-link" class="urlextern" title="http://wiki.openwrt.org/toh/start#tp-link"  rel="nofollow">http://wiki.openwrt.org/toh/start#tp-link</a> → Loooong and wiiiide table. While scrolling down, table headers get out of sight → Difficult to identify the meaning of a column, when headers are out of sight.</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Adjust width of wiki page editing window to allow fullscreen editing on 1920px wide monitors<br/>
The current restrictive setting and the resulting line breaks do not exactly help in editing the source code of wide tables.<br/>
Full width only neccessary in editing mode. Can there be done $something with <abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr>?</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Install dokuwiki plugin prettytables <a href="https://www.dokuwiki.org/plugin:prettytables" class="urlextern" title="https://www.dokuwiki.org/plugin:prettytables"  rel="nofollow">https://www.dokuwiki.org/plugin:prettytables</a><br/>
<strong>Note:</strong> Can be a great help in making tables readable in the source code. However, it has it&#039;s limits: Editing extremely wide tables does not lead to the desired effect. I use it myself to keep tables source code readable and easily editable.</div>
</li>
</ul>

</div>

<h3 class="sectionedit7" id="device_pages">Device pages</h3>
<div class="level3">

<p>
<em>Please link to forum threads or wiki pages; put links here and content on wiki pages.</em>
</p>
<ul>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Device page template</strong> needed</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <a href="../meta/template_device" class="urlextern" title="http://wiki.openwrt.org/meta/template_device"  rel="nofollow">http://wiki.openwrt.org/meta/template_device</a> (is this complete? does it look like it should? Changes needed? …) → to be discussed</div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <strong>What can we learn from others?</strong> → collect good/bad examples for toh&#039;s (freetz / wehavemorefun / dd-wrt / …) and put links here</div>
<ul>
<li class="level3"><div class="li"> <a href="http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box_Fon_WLAN_7570" class="urlextern" title="http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box_Fon_WLAN_7570"  rel="nofollow">http://www.wehavemorefun.de/fritzbox/FRITZ!Box_Fon_WLAN_7570</a></div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Template to be applied to all existing (most important ones first) and future pages</div>
<ul>
<li class="level3"><div class="li"> Who does this for existing device pages?</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Finalize transition from oldwiki</strong></div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Bad Example: <a href="../toh/samsung/smt-g3xx0" class="urlextern" title="http://wiki.openwrt.org/toh/samsung/smt-g3xx0"  rel="nofollow">http://wiki.openwrt.org/toh/samsung/smt-g3xx0</a> → &quot;Please transfer the informations from the old wiki pages SMT-G3010, SMT-G3210 and SMT-G3220 into this page. Thank you.&quot;; Last edited 2013/11/20 → transition should not take forever.</div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Check old vs. new wiki page, transfer content as needed, check for correctness, check if up to date, then remove the note &quot;Please transfer the informations…&quot;.</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Which pages need to be updated?</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> How can we easily filter for pages that need attention?</div>
<ul>
<li class="level3"><div class="li"> <strong>tag</strong> them with e.g. <code>needs_overhaul</code>, <code>missing_info</code>, … (please make more suggestions for this tag)</div>
</li>
<li class="level3"><div class="li"> …? (please add other proposals)</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> What information needs to be updated?</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> <strong>tagging</strong> is not updated/consistent, and does not really &quot;work&quot;</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> Check for syntax, grammar, spelling</div>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Prioritize</strong> updating pages according user interest</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Prerequisite: statistics / user/device/$whatever survey</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="level1"><div class="li"> <strong>Add general pictures</strong> for each device (front/back/[side only if buttons/connectors/… shown/Manuf. label])</div>
<ul>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Media manager → <code>toh/&lt;manufacturer&gt;/&lt;model&gt;-&lt;version&gt;-&lt;front|back|label|pcb|…&gt;.jpg|png</code></div>
</li>
<li class="level2"><div class="li"> Size (px/kB) restrictions?</div>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

</div>

